1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:18,530
So I just thought I'd start with, just in case there are some questions about the actual practice.

2
00:00:18,550 --> 00:00:19,472
Are there any questions?

3
00:00:25,719 --> 00:00:25,899
No?

4
00:00:26,099 --> 00:00:27,861
Everybody's perfectly clear and proper.

5
00:00:29,815 --> 00:00:32,079
I can't see everybody when I'm on this.

6
00:00:33,179 --> 00:00:38,228
You'll have to put your microphone on.

7
00:00:38,247 --> 00:00:39,229
No, no questions.

8
00:00:39,570 --> 00:00:40,972
Fantastic.

9
00:00:40,991 --> 00:00:41,973
Well, that's pretty easy then.

10
00:00:44,938 --> 00:00:48,664
So, just the usual reminders.

11
00:00:55,335 --> 00:00:58,219
We have to ask ourselves, you know, what was the Buddha's

12
00:00:59,143 --> 00:01:28,947
discovery and when we go back through his life we can see that he tried all the various techniques that were there present at the time sort of very concentrated states that we call absorption to fasting controlling your food intake on the understanding that the body was the problem and if you could just draw the body down

13
00:01:29,536 --> 00:01:36,603
then all the temptations that come with the body would disappear.

14
00:01:37,364 --> 00:01:42,730
So he just got very thin and presumably almost died.

15
00:01:42,790 --> 00:01:45,974
I don't know, but he definitely got very thin.

16
00:01:46,974 --> 00:01:54,442
So he was a man of his time, you know, even though we see him as extraordinary.

17
00:01:55,683 --> 00:01:57,525
There was a time of great ferment.

18
00:01:57,546 --> 00:01:59,408
I mean, it's known as the Axial Age.

19
00:02:00,112 --> 00:02:07,662
And the Brahminical tradition was producing all these new scriptures.

20
00:02:10,284 --> 00:02:13,729
And there was the Jain leader, too, who was a contemporary of the Buddha.

21
00:02:13,968 --> 00:02:24,822
And there were six other teachers at the time whom the Buddha had to contend with, one of them being what we would recognize these days as a materialist.

22
00:02:28,395 --> 00:02:32,699
So it was in that sort of melee that the Buddha was working.

23
00:02:33,580 --> 00:02:36,544
Now, just as these days, I mean, Trump isn't extraordinary.

24
00:02:36,563 --> 00:02:42,588
He's just an expression of our neoliberal situation.

25
00:02:43,790 --> 00:02:47,493
Without that situation, Trump would never have appeared.

26
00:02:48,495 --> 00:02:49,915
So it's the same with the Buddha.

27
00:02:50,075 --> 00:02:55,921
He's the flower of this enormous investigation that was going on at that time into

28
00:02:56,475 --> 00:03:01,164
into consciousness, into afterlife, all the things that were obsessing people.

29
00:03:03,949 --> 00:03:13,948
And what he discovered was that by turning inward, so up until then, seemingly he's trying to escape.

30
00:03:14,048 --> 00:03:16,012
He's trying to escape the suffering of life.

31
00:03:16,111 --> 00:03:20,560
He's trying to escape rebirth, this problem of constant reincarnation.

32
00:03:22,919 --> 00:03:26,485
And when all that fails and he's sitting under a tree, he does have this memory.

33
00:03:26,745 --> 00:03:32,995
And as far as I know, this is the only true biographical memory.

34
00:03:33,455 --> 00:03:36,161
Not biological, autobiographical.

35
00:03:37,342 --> 00:03:40,067
This is the only true biographical memory.

36
00:03:40,789 --> 00:03:42,973
peace in the whole of the scriptures.

37
00:03:43,073 --> 00:03:45,215
Everything else we can presume was made up.

38
00:03:45,294 --> 00:03:53,324
All that business about him being a king, the son of a king, and having these three gardens that he would go to and all that stuff.

39
00:03:53,725 --> 00:03:59,072
But the one point that seems to be true is this memory.

40
00:03:59,352 --> 00:04:07,421
So it's a kernel memory of him watching his father doing a ploughing ceremony, which opened up the ploughing season.

41
00:04:08,026 --> 00:04:18,898
His father was the head man, basically, of a tribe which is situated in North India, now sort of into the border of Nepal.

42
00:04:20,079 --> 00:04:29,668
And what he remembers is sitting there, watching his father with that sense of curiosity.

43
00:04:30,951 --> 00:04:31,992
And he's absorbed.

44
00:04:32,814 --> 00:04:35,057
He's absorbed into that process.

45
00:04:35,098 --> 00:04:36,579
He's not thinking about it.

46
00:04:36,959 --> 00:04:38,401
He's not reflecting on it.

47
00:04:38,742 --> 00:04:39,624
He's just watching.

48
00:04:39,863 --> 00:04:40,665
He's just watching.

49
00:04:42,447 --> 00:04:45,951
And at the end of that watching, he comes to understand what his father's doing.

50
00:04:47,514 --> 00:04:52,180
So, you know, I position him somewhere around about the age of seven, seven, eight, something like that.

51
00:04:56,206 --> 00:04:56,966
And somehow.

52
00:04:57,773 --> 00:05:03,000
That opened up to him a way of looking which was not conceptual.

53
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:05,862
So that's our real problem.

54
00:05:06,985 --> 00:05:16,295
Everything we look at, everything we taste, everything we smell, everything we touch comes with a concept.

55
00:05:18,920 --> 00:05:25,687
That concept can be very simple like hot, or it can be huge like democracy.

56
00:05:26,461 --> 00:05:27,923
But it's conceptual.

57
00:05:28,182 --> 00:05:35,333
It's an idea, right, which we then plunk onto the experience.

58
00:05:37,055 --> 00:05:48,812
So we never, I won't say never, but usually, more often than not, we experience things through a concept.

59
00:05:50,615 --> 00:05:52,617
Now, it's not as though we want to get rid of concepts.

60
00:05:53,338 --> 00:05:55,742
You need to know when something is hot and when it's cold.

61
00:05:56,396 --> 00:06:04,846
But it's drawing that attention back down out of the conceiving mind, out of conceptualizing things.

62
00:06:05,406 --> 00:06:07,148
It's extraordinarily difficult.

63
00:06:09,211 --> 00:06:16,098
And the only way to do it is to drive the attention towards what we're actually experiencing in this present moment.

64
00:06:19,261 --> 00:06:22,725
Conceiving the idea of concepts

65
00:06:23,262 --> 00:06:52,880
what the mind does is it gives us a sort of reality that we can live with take time i mean we have a memory of things past and an idea of things future and that somehow time is a sort of funnel that we're passing through we're in time in time but actually that's not what's happening is it what's happening is

66
00:06:53,401 --> 00:07:01,411
Things are arising and passing away in this present moment, and there is no power.

67
00:07:01,730 --> 00:07:06,576
Whatever there was, even a nanosecond ago, has completely disappeared.

68
00:07:07,838 --> 00:07:09,901
And what's coming in the future, I haven't a clue.

69
00:07:10,581 --> 00:07:23,036
Generally speaking, because we're in a situation like this, like ours in the West, which is fairly peaceful, we don't get that sense of insecurity.

70
00:07:24,416 --> 00:07:33,329
But if you were living now in one of the war zones in Ukraine, you never know when one of these bombs are just going to blow you to pieces.

71
00:07:34,290 --> 00:07:45,125
You're living right on the edge, which brings you right into the present moment when you're like that.

72
00:07:45,146 --> 00:07:54,237
And it's this effort to begin to experience things before we have an idea of what it is.

73
00:07:56,428 --> 00:08:00,896
that allows us to see things like impermanence, because we're right there.

74
00:08:01,016 --> 00:08:03,439
The mind is always constructing.

75
00:08:04,901 --> 00:08:06,283
It's always constructing.

76
00:08:08,447 --> 00:08:10,730
So that's the purpose of vipassana.

77
00:08:10,769 --> 00:08:13,634
Vipassana, remember, means to see things as they really are.

78
00:08:14,134 --> 00:08:17,218
The passana means to see, passana, passati.

79
00:08:17,759 --> 00:08:20,343
And the V is just a strengthener, to really see it.

80
00:08:28,559 --> 00:08:36,868
And just that effort to keep the attention on exactly what we're feeling, exactly what we're experiencing, the breath.

81
00:08:37,208 --> 00:08:56,169
Take the breath, for instance, right, to stay with it and to drive the attention right into it, right into it with that sense of curiosity, which is asking, am I actually seeing this as it really is or is there some conceiving going on?

82
00:08:58,293 --> 00:09:21,820
in the zen tradition of um korea the zen tradition of korea uh they have this thing called the wadu which just means what is it what is this what is this and it's just a way of centering that attention constantly asking ourselves right am i seeing this the way it is now

83
00:09:22,171 --> 00:09:29,380
When I say constantly asking ourselves, I'm not saying that we should be there asking ourselves constantly, what is this?

84
00:09:30,481 --> 00:09:32,504
That is just driving you potty.

85
00:09:32,524 --> 00:09:33,385
It's an attitude.

86
00:09:33,546 --> 00:09:45,883
It's an attitude that we're trying to develop of a sort of radical doubt about ourselves as to our ability to see what's actually happening.

87
00:09:47,062 --> 00:09:49,424
It's an honest doubt.

88
00:09:51,388 --> 00:09:54,732
It's asking ourselves, am I seeing this as it really is?

89
00:09:55,134 --> 00:10:00,140
On a grander scale, am I understanding the world as it really is?

90
00:10:00,260 --> 00:10:06,791
Do I understand where we are historically, where we are economically?

91
00:10:07,350 --> 00:10:09,794
It's like a general interest question.

92
00:10:10,214 --> 00:10:16,460
But in terms of the practice of ourselves, am I actually seeing myself as I really am?

93
00:10:16,759 --> 00:10:18,140
That's the question.

94
00:10:19,562 --> 00:10:31,673
And this effort to draw ourselves into the present moment opens up the possibility of really experiencing the fact that we are totally momentary.

95
00:10:33,274 --> 00:10:34,456
Totally momentary.

96
00:10:35,336 --> 00:10:39,681
You know, we're arising the whole thing, the whole body, mind, everything.

97
00:10:39,998 --> 00:10:43,562
It's arising and passing away at the moment.

98
00:10:43,582 --> 00:10:58,341
This has a systemic effect because it makes us realize that the whole thing about holding on to something, keeping it, trying to stop things moving, trying to stop things changing is a fool's game.

99
00:10:58,520 --> 00:11:00,163
It just creates frustration.

100
00:11:00,222 --> 00:11:03,086
It creates it creates a sorrow.

101
00:11:03,826 --> 00:11:14,586
Even in relationships, you know, to try and hold a relationship as it is, you know, you're not the person I began to live with, you're not the person I married and all that.

102
00:11:14,865 --> 00:11:22,559
Those sorts of statements don't make any sense within a situation which is in a state of continuous change.

103
00:11:25,392 --> 00:11:36,163
So that trying to hold ourselves as we are, where we feel comfortable, trying to hold the other person where they are, that sense of trying to control, you see, trying to control.

104
00:11:36,844 --> 00:11:39,447
And underneath that, underneath that, what do you find?

105
00:11:39,826 --> 00:11:40,528
You find fear.

106
00:11:41,749 --> 00:11:43,831
Fear, right?

107
00:11:43,850 --> 00:11:48,336
At the fundamental base of our existence, you'll find fear.

108
00:11:48,895 --> 00:11:49,496
Fear of what?

109
00:11:49,777 --> 00:11:50,437
Fear of death.

110
00:11:51,413 --> 00:11:55,438
It's always underneath everything we're doing, this fear of death.

111
00:11:56,120 --> 00:12:03,289
And death, in all its aspects of loss, right, every moment is a momentary death.

112
00:12:03,951 --> 00:12:08,317
Every time you lose something, you've lost something that was part of you.

113
00:12:08,376 --> 00:12:15,187
Even if you only owned it, you didn't describe yourself by it, you didn't identify by it, but it was part of you.

114
00:12:15,226 --> 00:12:17,370
It's a little death, a mini death.

115
00:12:18,328 --> 00:12:27,799
And that fear, if it's not brought into our lives, begins to affect us in all these peculiar ways.

116
00:12:28,400 --> 00:12:34,868
During the pandemic, you'll notice, I'm sure some of you noticed or some of you read about it.

117
00:12:34,927 --> 00:12:38,432
Everybody went out and bought loads of toilet paper.

118
00:12:40,735 --> 00:12:41,716
What an amazing thing.

119
00:12:42,297 --> 00:12:47,863
There was here, there was, I met somebody and they'd actually, I think it was a bit cheeky, a bit,

120
00:12:48,231 --> 00:12:57,462
There was this elderly woman and she was walked out with a whole tray full, a whole one of those trolleys full of toilet paper.

121
00:12:57,763 --> 00:12:59,205
And he made a big comment on it.

122
00:12:59,225 --> 00:13:02,168
There were all sorts of people around and made a comment on it, you know.

123
00:13:04,071 --> 00:13:04,410
Why?

124
00:13:04,471 --> 00:13:17,866
Well, if you read about what the suppression, the repression of death does to us, you'll notice that we make these connections, right?

125
00:13:18,116 --> 00:13:21,059
with shit, excuse the word, with money.

126
00:13:21,179 --> 00:13:22,562
That's why money is dirty.

127
00:13:22,621 --> 00:13:28,207
Somehow we construe money as being part of death, a part of loss.

128
00:13:29,649 --> 00:13:37,057
And so not bringing that death into our lives, right, is really undermining us.

129
00:13:37,136 --> 00:13:39,399
It's not opening us up.

130
00:13:39,919 --> 00:13:47,989
It's making us clamp down with fear so that in the morning, if you were to say to yourself, I might not live

131
00:13:48,711 --> 00:14:15,293
whole of this day i might actually die or i might see the first signs of a terminal illness now at first you might think well if i do that i'm just going to get depressed but actually the opposite happens by bringing death as a as a possibility in our lives at all times right we don't know the hour or the day jesus christ yet as soon as we bring that into our life

132
00:14:16,437 --> 00:14:23,563
The effect is to make us realize how amazing life is, how we have this consciousness in the first place.

133
00:14:23,884 --> 00:14:25,885
How is it there is something anyway?

134
00:14:26,886 --> 00:14:37,038
The fact that there is this, I'm looking out onto a scene where there's the sun shining and the snow is full of this whiteness and it's a rare occasion these days.

135
00:14:37,597 --> 00:14:39,900
And there's beauty out there.

136
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:42,342
One can feel it.

137
00:14:42,947 --> 00:14:56,910
And that beauty and the joys of life become more accented when you recognize that everything's transient and that ultimately it'll all disappear and I'll disappear.

138
00:14:58,072 --> 00:15:08,009
So all these things, when you're looking into your practice, when you're actually diving in to your feelings, to your sensations, to your breath,

139
00:15:08,293 --> 00:15:16,354
and getting down there to see that it's just made up of little bits and pieces, little sensations arising and passing away.

140
00:15:16,975 --> 00:15:19,822
All this is part of seeing impermanence.

141
00:15:22,469 --> 00:15:33,388
And as we go deeper into this impermanence and see what the suffering arises by not accepting impermanence, we're getting down to that deep level of fear.

142
00:15:33,408 --> 00:15:36,974
And that fear is pointing to something.

143
00:15:37,033 --> 00:15:41,642
It's pointing to a concept about who I am.

144
00:15:42,230 --> 00:15:47,697
And that the deepest fundamental problem of our existence is identity.

145
00:15:48,219 --> 00:15:53,966
And I've noticed that now some of you will know Sutter Central on the website.

146
00:15:54,006 --> 00:15:55,549
It's a great site.

147
00:15:56,551 --> 00:15:59,936
He's done this Sujata, this Ajahn Sujata.

148
00:15:59,975 --> 00:16:05,144
He's done all the scriptures now, which he seems to have translated.

149
00:16:05,203 --> 00:16:10,751
Some of his translations are a little bit, as you would say, inventive.

150
00:16:11,339 --> 00:16:11,940
But they're good.

151
00:16:12,200 --> 00:16:12,701
They're good.

152
00:16:13,422 --> 00:16:18,330
And I've noticed that he's now translating delusion as identity.

153
00:16:19,171 --> 00:16:19,412
Right.

154
00:16:19,572 --> 00:16:20,854
Finally, right.

155
00:16:20,874 --> 00:16:22,035
Actually pointing to it.

156
00:16:22,556 --> 00:16:23,958
That's the root of it.

157
00:16:23,979 --> 00:16:34,936
That's the whole that discourse that the Buddha gives his second discourse, which allows his other which allows the five companions of his to become fully liberated.

158
00:16:35,375 --> 00:16:35,876
Right.

159
00:16:35,897 --> 00:16:36,879
Now, that's not magic.

160
00:16:36,938 --> 00:16:39,101
Remember, they'd been practicing like him.

161
00:16:39,436 --> 00:16:50,907
for years with these absorption states and with the more self-mortification things about not eating and all that sort of stuff.

162
00:16:50,927 --> 00:16:53,249
And they all become liberated after this talk.

163
00:16:53,288 --> 00:16:54,350
And what's the talk on?

164
00:16:54,370 --> 00:16:56,913
It's the talk about not self.

165
00:16:57,033 --> 00:17:04,559
And what that talk is simply saying is, is the idea of me as a person, is that real?

166
00:17:04,680 --> 00:17:06,422
Can I substantiate it?

167
00:17:08,241 --> 00:17:10,244
And the first thing he points to is control.

168
00:17:10,766 --> 00:17:16,556
So as you're doing your meditation inside yourself, you can see that things are just happening.

169
00:17:17,016 --> 00:17:19,200
You're not telling the breath to breathe.

170
00:17:19,220 --> 00:17:24,167
You're not telling your heart to express its sadnesses or its happinesses.

171
00:17:24,528 --> 00:17:28,555
You're not saying to your mind, now think about this, think about that.

172
00:17:29,076 --> 00:17:30,739
It's just all happening.

173
00:17:31,192 --> 00:17:40,188
And that sense of not control begins to take away this idea that I must be this psychophysical organism.

174
00:17:40,407 --> 00:17:41,750
That's what you're undermining.

175
00:17:43,875 --> 00:17:52,128
And then when you look at impermanence, you can see that whenever you hold on to something, it's going to cause suffering because it's not going to be there.

176
00:17:52,249 --> 00:17:53,070
It's going to change.

177
00:17:53,191 --> 00:17:54,313
Something's going to happen.

178
00:17:55,188 --> 00:18:04,778
So it's this process of vipassana, which we, you know, the more we can really devote ourselves to doing it properly.

179
00:18:05,478 --> 00:18:07,601
Often in our practice, we get lazy.

180
00:18:07,820 --> 00:18:16,569
And I'm just as much guilty of that as anybody else, where you sit and you start off with a good intention, but then the mind wanders.

181
00:18:16,609 --> 00:18:19,913
And before you know it, you're worrying about this and you're thinking about that.

182
00:18:21,361 --> 00:18:36,113
So that opening gambit where we sit and we really talk to ourselves and say, come on, settle down, calm, be peaceful, draw your attention into the breath, etc., etc., and be aware of

183
00:18:36,531 --> 00:18:38,555
what mental state you're beginning with.

184
00:18:38,654 --> 00:18:43,961
If it's a very agitated state, perhaps a scan through the body might be very helpful.

185
00:18:45,124 --> 00:18:51,192
Going down if you are agitated, coming up if you're slothful, it raises energy.

186
00:18:52,054 --> 00:19:03,670
And if we acknowledge the mental state that we start with and work with it, and then we have that steadiness of attention to actually turn it into something we're investigating.

187
00:19:06,755 --> 00:19:09,978
So that's what we're actually practicing.

188
00:19:10,218 --> 00:19:16,724
So the practice and an ordinary daily life, right?

189
00:19:16,744 --> 00:19:19,326
They sort of shave into each other.

190
00:19:19,406 --> 00:19:20,808
They move into each other.

191
00:19:21,588 --> 00:19:33,461
So that, for instance, at the end of a work, a piece of work, or you've done a bit of gardening, or you've done this, or you've made a cup of tea, just to stop for a moment and just recognize that's gone, that's finished.

192
00:19:33,480 --> 00:19:34,382
That's the end.

193
00:19:34,602 --> 00:19:35,563
It's not there anymore.

194
00:19:35,914 --> 00:19:39,398
And then just to relax into this present moment, just to stop.

195
00:19:41,101 --> 00:19:43,563
And then the next intention comes.

196
00:19:43,583 --> 00:19:45,905
And you empower that intention, right?

197
00:19:46,405 --> 00:19:49,750
And that way, there's a sense of at least guiding your life.

198
00:19:50,210 --> 00:19:51,771
I don't want to use the word controlled.

199
00:19:51,811 --> 00:19:53,012
You're not controlled.

200
00:19:53,032 --> 00:19:59,400
You're guiding your life in a way that is going to lead to greater happiness, greater contentment.

201
00:20:00,121 --> 00:20:05,567
There's a section in the Dhammapada, which is a collection of all these verses that the Buddha made up.

202
00:20:06,796 --> 00:20:12,241
It's totally devoted to making the self happy.

203
00:20:12,902 --> 00:20:18,647
This self that we feel, it can actually make itself happy.

204
00:20:18,807 --> 00:20:23,292
That's why we practice metta, we practice joy, we practice compassion.

205
00:20:23,313 --> 00:20:26,875
The practice is to make ourselves happy, but not excited.

206
00:20:27,237 --> 00:20:29,398
There's another confusion we get into.

207
00:20:29,980 --> 00:20:32,382
So excitement is that sort of thing.

208
00:20:32,699 --> 00:20:57,761
level of agitation that comes when we're feeding into a desire and the unfortunate consequence of that is that you can't feed it enough and it keeps coming back keeps coming back so one of the things about happiness and joy which is coming from the goodness of the heart is that once it goes there's no anchoring after it and it always comes with a sense of calmness

209
00:20:58,045 --> 00:21:09,960
So there are all these indications in the Buddha's teachings that our practice is supposed to actually make us more contented and happy in all of our daily life.

210
00:21:11,182 --> 00:21:13,884
And that's taken over time, right?

211
00:21:14,326 --> 00:21:18,490
You can't measure it by week by week, because some weeks are awful and some weeks are pretty good.

212
00:21:18,911 --> 00:21:26,601
But over a measure of time, you can see that your life is becoming more settled, more calm, more peaceful, more joyful.

213
00:21:27,744 --> 00:21:35,933
And the practice is what is, shall we say, pushing you a little, just pushing you a little to look a bit more deeply.

214
00:21:37,394 --> 00:21:55,795
And if we can bring that sense of just being, just stopping every so often, and then noting that intention, making sure the intention is, as the Buddha would say, to our own benefit, for the benefit of ourselves, for the benefit of someone else, or for both our benefits.

215
00:21:57,361 --> 00:22:03,808
And that's what makes work so meaningful is when you can see it as a benefit, when you can see it as a service.

216
00:22:04,589 --> 00:22:06,432
I've just watched a wonderful film.

217
00:22:06,571 --> 00:22:07,113
Just a minute.

218
00:22:11,137 --> 00:22:17,005
It's by the it's by the German director, Wim Wenders.

219
00:22:17,065 --> 00:22:17,545
I don't know.

220
00:22:17,585 --> 00:22:19,867
Can I get that on the screen?

221
00:22:19,948 --> 00:22:20,888
It's a bit dodgy.

222
00:22:20,909 --> 00:22:21,309
Here we go.

223
00:22:21,410 --> 00:22:22,250
Perfect Days.

224
00:22:23,112 --> 00:22:23,853
Perfect Days.

225
00:22:23,932 --> 00:22:24,814
Oh, here we go.

226
00:22:24,834 --> 00:22:26,056
No, go again.

227
00:22:26,076 --> 00:22:27,317
It's called Perfect Days.

228
00:22:27,719 --> 00:22:33,326
And it's basically about this man.

229
00:22:34,188 --> 00:22:41,137
I mean, we find out more about him when he goes, but he basically cleans toilets and he fills his day.

230
00:22:41,538 --> 00:22:48,248
He fills his part-time day with a bit of photography, a bit of music, looking after trees, et cetera, et cetera.

231
00:22:49,269 --> 00:22:54,958
And you can get the feeling that here is someone who has dropped his

232
00:22:55,326 --> 00:23:02,174
dropped out of a type of life which was stressful and has now found a way of just being.

233
00:23:02,575 --> 00:23:09,563
And he's taken a very simple job to maintain that sort of connectedness with society.

234
00:23:10,324 --> 00:23:13,307
By the way, the toilets in Japan are amazing.

235
00:23:13,586 --> 00:23:16,490
I mean, they are architectural beauties.

236
00:23:18,532 --> 00:23:21,115
It tells you a lot about the Japanese, yeah.

237
00:23:21,135 --> 00:23:22,837
And their toilets are something else.

238
00:23:23,057 --> 00:23:24,759
So you have to look that up.

239
00:23:25,009 --> 00:23:30,559
on AI to find out what the Japanese toilets are like.

240
00:23:31,942 --> 00:23:40,517
So just to recap, so we're practicing to see the three characteristics of existence.

241
00:23:40,777 --> 00:23:41,898
That's what they're called.

242
00:23:42,380 --> 00:23:45,464
The first one is to see the process of desire.

243
00:23:46,238 --> 00:23:48,961
And it's a wrong type of desire.

244
00:23:49,082 --> 00:23:54,528
It's the desire that wants to cling, that wants to have it all, that wants more.

245
00:23:54,848 --> 00:23:55,048
Right.

246
00:23:55,630 --> 00:24:00,736
In our society, that word more before it used to be more of something.

247
00:24:00,996 --> 00:24:02,458
You know, I want more chocolate.

248
00:24:02,478 --> 00:24:03,479
I want more ice cream.

249
00:24:03,499 --> 00:24:05,442
But now it's just more.

250
00:24:05,781 --> 00:24:06,303
There's more.

251
00:24:07,463 --> 00:24:10,508
More of everything I've got and more of what I haven't got.

252
00:24:11,180 --> 00:24:22,313
And then there's this process of seeing impermanence and to bring that into our daily lives all the time, to see that everything comes to an end, everything comes to an end.

253
00:24:22,333 --> 00:24:33,665
And then finally, this idea of self, not self, of constantly questioning who this person is, who am I, what am I, right?

254
00:24:33,685 --> 00:24:36,450
Just constantly questioning that.

255
00:24:37,150 --> 00:24:39,313
Now, in that process,

256
00:24:40,188 --> 00:24:52,784
Unwittingly, well, or in fact, quite self-consciously, we're drawing something away from its confusion with this psychophysical organism.

257
00:24:54,066 --> 00:24:55,347
And it's this awareness.

258
00:24:56,769 --> 00:25:01,434
Every time you're aware of something, you're pushing it away from your awareness.

259
00:25:02,276 --> 00:25:05,840
You're becoming more aware of what the awareness is.

260
00:25:06,512 --> 00:25:20,905
And it might be that at some point in your practice, either on retreat or even in daily life, if the attention is quite clear, you might just become aware of being that awareness.

261
00:25:21,405 --> 00:25:26,131
So you're up here, as it were, and you're being aware of being aware.

262
00:25:26,171 --> 00:25:27,090
Right.

263
00:25:27,731 --> 00:25:31,474
And you can glance back in, glance back into that awareness.

264
00:25:31,515 --> 00:25:34,478
And when you come out, you can ask yourself, what's it made of?

265
00:25:34,896 --> 00:25:36,038
What do I see there?

266
00:25:36,358 --> 00:25:37,380
What did I feel?

267
00:25:37,740 --> 00:25:38,520
What did I know?

268
00:25:38,560 --> 00:25:43,045
And you might surprise yourself, right, to find out what that is.

269
00:25:45,106 --> 00:25:49,852
That's just a little exercise that I've culled from the Mahayana tradition.

270
00:25:50,932 --> 00:25:56,778
So our practice is onward leading.

271
00:25:57,420 --> 00:25:58,361
That's the important thing.

272
00:25:58,882 --> 00:26:04,126
And even though we have dips in it, even though sometimes you look back and you think, well, I haven't changed that much.

273
00:26:05,490 --> 00:26:12,443
That's only because of expectation, of expecting the practice to be a magical thing.

274
00:26:12,986 --> 00:26:16,792
But the Buddha said, you know, he didn't disguise it.

275
00:26:17,073 --> 00:26:19,417
He didn't say it was easy, right?

276
00:26:19,577 --> 00:26:23,285
And I always like to quote this person who asked him.

277
00:26:23,306 --> 00:26:26,672
He said, you know, this training you're giving us is very hard.

278
00:26:27,157 --> 00:26:33,525
And the Buddha said, well, yeah, he said, but in the end, you achieve nibbana, right, which is variously described.

279
00:26:33,566 --> 00:26:38,932
But one description would be without that unwholesome desire.

280
00:26:39,873 --> 00:26:42,236
And he says, yeah, but then you get to nibbana.

281
00:26:42,256 --> 00:26:44,198
And then the guy says, yeah, but so what?

282
00:26:45,118 --> 00:26:47,201
So what's this nibbana business?

283
00:26:47,801 --> 00:26:52,288
He says, when you get there, he says, you are contented and with it happy.

284
00:26:53,148 --> 00:26:56,051
You are contented and with it happy.

285
00:26:56,587 --> 00:27:01,474
And the word for that, the words for that are tutti succuahati.

286
00:27:01,494 --> 00:27:04,380
So I always say tutti frutti and succuahati.

287
00:27:04,759 --> 00:27:22,646
So our practice is leading us towards a contentment with life, a general happiness, and eventually this understanding of a transcendental state, this experience of a transcendental state that we call nibbana.

288
00:27:24,719 --> 00:27:37,327
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance that I have not caused even greater confusion and that by your practice you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

